{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654654"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:54:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:54:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18627"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18627"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11359"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76497"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11359"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18627"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61994"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"10240"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26360"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26365"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26373"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76497"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe movements of inversion and eversion at the foot are essential for adapting to uneven surfaces during walking and maintaining balance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary muscle responsible for foot inversion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Extensor digitorum longus","Peroneus brevis","Tibialis posterior","Peroneus longus","Tibialis anterior"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etibialis posterior\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary muscle responsible for foot inversion. It runs behind the medial malleolus and attaches to multiple bones in the foot. When it contracts, it pulls the medial border of the foot upward, creating inversion.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeroneus longus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is an evertor of the foot, producing the opposite movement to inversion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeroneus brevis\u003C/strong\u003E - Like peroneus longus, this muscle produces eversion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETibialis anterior\u003C/strong\u003E - While this muscle assists with inversion, its primary action is dorsiflexion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensor digitorum longus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle primarily extends the toes and assists with dorsiflexion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe movement of inversion occurs primarily at the subtalar joint, where the talus articulates with the calcaneus. This joint allows the sole of the foot to face medially during inversion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inversion of the foot is primarily performed by the tibialis posterior muscle.","Eversion of the foot is primarily performed by the peroneus longus and brevis muscles.","The subtalar joint is the primary joint responsible for inversion and eversion movements."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61994"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18627"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61994","links":{"self":"htt